-- Australian Government Committed to Introducing a Mining Tax, Swan Says
-- Marion Rae
-- 2010-06-24T21:50:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-24/australian-government-committed-to-introducing-a-mining-tax-swan-says.html

          
          
             Australia will have a profits-based
mining tax under the Labor government led by Julia Gillard and
talks on details such as the 40 percent rate will begin again
with the resources industry, Deputy Prime Minister and Treasurer
Wayne Swan told Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio
today.  
 To contact the reporter on this story:
Marion Rae in Canberra at 
 mrae3@bloomberg.net   
          
          


  
     
       
     
           
                           
                 
                 
                                       
                                   
               
                        
           
                          June 25 (Bloomberg) -- Colin Whitehead, equity analyst at Fat Prophets, talks with Bloomberg's Rishaad Salamat about the potential implications of Julia Gillard's appointment as Australian prime minister for the government's proposed mining profits tax.
     Gillard, who was sworn in yesterday after ousting Kevin Rudd, said she is willing to negotiate on the tax with mining companies. Whitehead, speaking from Sydney, also discusses the outlook for Australian mining stocks and the global economy.  (Source: Bloomberg)  
                   
    

                 
           
                           
                 
                 
                                       
                                   
               
                        
           
                          June 25 (Bloomberg) -- Craig Ferguson, a currency hedge fund manager at Antipodean Capital Management, talks with Bloomberg's Haslinda Amin about his forecast for the Australian dollar.
     Ferguson, speaking from Melbourne, also discusses the implications of Julia Gillard's appointment as Australia's prime minister on the nation's currency and proposed mining profits tax, and the outlook for the yuan. (Source: Bloomberg)  
                           

     
